# Multithreaded FizzBuzz in C++

Here's a complete implementation using threads and mutexes:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
#include <mutex>
#include <vector>

std::mutex printMutex;

void fizzBuzz(int start, int end, int step, int totalThreads) {
    for (int i = start; i <= end; i += step) {
        std::string output;

        if (i % 15 == 0) {
            output = "FizzBuzz";
        } else if (i % 3 == 0) {
            output = "Fizz";
        } else if (i % 5 == 0) {
            output = "Buzz";
        } else {
            output = std::to_string(i);
        }

        // Lock before printing
        {
            std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(printMutex);
            std::cout << output << std::endl;
        }
    }
}

int main() {
    int n = 100;
    int numThreads = 4;

    std::vector<std::thread> threads;

    // Create and launch threads
    for (int t = 0; t < numThreads; ++t) {
        threads.emplace_back(fizzBuzz, t + 1, n, numThreads, numThreads);
    }

    // Wait for all threads to complete
    for (auto& thread : threads) {
        thread.join();
    }

    return 0;
}
```

## Explanation

1. **Mutex**: `std::mutex printMutex` protects the critical section (printing)

2. **Lock Guard**: `std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(printMutex)` automatically locks and unlocks the mutex using RAII

3. **Thread Division**: Each thread handles every `numThreads`-th number:
   - Thread 0: 1, 5, 9, 13...
   - Thread 1: 2, 6, 10, 14...
   - Thread 2: 3, 7, 11, 15...
   - Thread 3: 4, 8, 12, 16...

4. **Join**: `thread.join()` waits for each thread to finish before exiting

## Compile and Run

```bash
g++ -std=c++11 -pthread -o fizzbuzz fizzbuzz.cpp
./fizzbuzz
```

## Alternative: With Unique Lock

For more control, you can use `std::unique_lock`:

```cpp
{
    std::unique_lock<std::mutex> lock(printMutex);
    std::cout << output << std::endl;
    // lock.unlock(); // Optional explicit unlock
} // Automatically unlocked here
```

Both approaches ensure thread-safe printing without race conditions!

# Longest Increasing Subsequence (LIS)

Here are a few implementations with different approaches:

## 1. **Dynamic Programming Approach (O(n²))**

```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

std::vector<int> longestIncreasingSubsequence(const std::vector<int>& arr) {
    if (arr.empty()) return {};

    int n = arr.size();
    std::vector<int> dp(n, 1);           // dp[i] = length of LIS ending at i
    std::vector<int> parent(n, -1);      // to track the sequence

    // Build dp array
    for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < i; j++) {
            if (arr[j] < arr[i] && dp[j] + 1 > dp[i]) {
                dp[i] = dp[j] + 1;
                parent[i] = j;
            }
        }
    }

    // Find index of maximum length
    int maxIndex = std::max_element(dp.begin(), dp.end()) - dp.begin();

    // Reconstruct the sequence
    std::vector<int> result;
    int idx = maxIndex;
    while (idx != -1) {
        result.push_back(arr[idx]);
        idx = parent[idx];
    }

    std::reverse(result.begin(), result.end());
    return result;
}
```

## 2. **Binary Search Approach (O(n log n))**

```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

std::vector<int> longestIncreasingSubsequence(const std::vector<int>& arr) {
    if (arr.empty()) return {};

    std::vector<int> lis;
    std::vector<int> parent(arr.size(), -1);
    std::vector<int> lis_indices;

    for (int i = 0; i < arr.size(); i++) {
        auto it = std::lower_bound(lis.begin(), lis.end(), arr[i]);
        int pos = it - lis.begin();

        if (pos == lis.size()) {
            lis.push_back(arr[i]);
            lis_indices.push_back(i);
        } else {
            lis[pos] = arr[i];
            lis_indices[pos] = i;
        }

        parent[i] = (pos > 0) ? lis_indices[pos - 1] : -1;
    }

    // Reconstruct sequence
    std::vector<int> result;
    int idx = lis_indices.back();
    while (idx != -1) {
        result.push_back(arr[idx]);
        idx = parent[idx];
    }

    std::reverse(result.begin(), result.end());
    return result;
}
```

## 3. **Simple Version (Returns only length)**

```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

int longestIncreasingSubsequenceLength(const std::vector<int>& arr) {
    if (arr.empty()) return 0;

    int n = arr.size();
    std::vector<int> dp(n, 1);

    for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < i; j++) {
            if (arr[j] < arr[i]) {
                dp[i] = std::max(dp[i], dp[j] + 1);
            }
        }
    }

    return *std::max_element(dp.begin(), dp.end());
}
```

## Usage Example:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    std::vector<int> numbers = {10, 9, 2, 5, 3, 7, 101, 18};

    auto result = longestIncreasingSubsequence(numbers);

    std::cout << "LIS: ";
    for (int num : result) {
        std::cout << num << " ";
    }
    std::cout << "\nLength: " << result.size() << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

**Output:**
```
LIS: 2 3 7 101 
Length: 4
```

## Comparison:

| Approach | Time | Space | Returns |
|----------|------|-------|---------|
| DP (O(n²)) | O(n²) | O(n) | Sequence |
| Binary Search | O(n log n) | O(n) | Sequence |
| Length Only | O(n²) | O(n) | Length |

Choose the **binary search approach** for better performance with larger datasets!

