# Multithreaded FizzBuzz with Mutexes

Here's a complete implementation in C++:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
#include <mutex>
#include <vector>

std::mutex print_mutex;

void fizzbuzz_worker(int start, int end, int step, int num_threads) {
    for (int i = start; i <= end; i += step) {
        std::string output;

        if (i % 15 == 0) {
            output = "FizzBuzz";
        } else if (i % 3 == 0) {
            output = "Fizz";
        } else if (i % 5 == 0) {
            output = "Buzz";
        } else {
            output = std::to_string(i);
        }

        // Lock mutex before printing
        {
            std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(print_mutex);
            std::cout << output << std::endl;
        }
    }
}

int main() {
    const int N = 100;
    const int NUM_THREADS = 4;

    std::vector<std::thread> threads;

    // Create worker threads
    for (int t = 0; t < NUM_THREADS; ++t) {
        threads.emplace_back(
            fizzbuzz_worker,
            t + 1,           // start
            N,               // end
            NUM_THREADS,     // step
            NUM_THREADS      // num_threads
        );
    }

    // Wait for all threads to complete
    for (auto& thread : threads) {
        thread.join();
    }

    return 0;
}
```

## How It Works

1. **Thread Division**: Each thread processes numbers with a stride equal to the number of threads:
   - Thread 0: 1, 5, 9, 13, ...
   - Thread 1: 2, 6, 10, 14, ...
   - Thread 2: 3, 7, 11, 15, ...
   - Thread 3: 4, 8, 12, 16, ...

2. **Mutex Protection**: The `std::lock_guard` ensures only one thread prints at a time, preventing interleaved output.

3. **RAII Pattern**: The lock automatically releases when `lock` goes out of scope.

## Alternative: Using `std::unique_lock` for More Control

```cpp
void fizzbuzz_worker(int start, int end, int step) {
    for (int i = start; i <= end; i += step) {
        std::string output = generate_output(i);

        std::unique_lock<std::mutex> lock(print_mutex);
        std::cout << output << std::endl;
        lock.unlock();  // Explicit unlock if needed
    }
}
```

## Compile and Run

```bash
g++ -std=c++11 -pthread -o fizzbuzz fizzbuzz.cpp
./fizzbuzz
```

## Output Example
```
1
2
Fizz
4
Buzz
Fizz
7
8
Fizz
Buzz
11
Fizz
13
14
FizzBuzz
...
```

The output order may vary between runs due to thread scheduling, but each number/FizzBuzz will be on its own line with no interleaving.

# CSS Code to Make All Text Boxes Visible

Here are several approaches depending on your needs:

## 1. **Basic Approach - Make Input Fields Visible**
```css
input[type="text"],
input[type="email"],
input[type="password"],
input[type="search"],
input[type="url"],
input[type="number"],
textarea,
select {
    visibility: visible !important;
    display: block !important;
    opacity: 1 !important;
}
```

## 2. **Comprehensive Approach - All Form Elements**
```css
/* Text inputs */
input[type="text"],
input[type="email"],
input[type="password"],
input[type="search"],
input[type="url"],
input[type="number"],
input[type="tel"],
textarea,
select,
.textbox,
.text-input {
    visibility: visible !important;
    display: block !important;
    opacity: 1 !important;
    pointer-events: auto !important;
    color: inherit !important;
}
```

## 3. **Universal Approach - All Elements**
```css
* {
    visibility: visible !important;
    opacity: 1 !important;
    display: block !important;
}
```

## 4. **Remove Hidden/Display:None Classes**
```css
.hidden,
.hide,
[hidden],
[style*="display: none"],
[style*="visibility: hidden"],
[style*="opacity: 0"] {
    display: block !important;
    visibility: visible !important;
    opacity: 1 !important;
}
```

## **Recommendation**
Use **Option 1 or 2** as they target specific elements without breaking page layout. Option 3 may cause layout issues since it affects all elements.

